T1  - Investment and financial asset accumulation
AU  - Whited, Toni M
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 1
IS  - 4
SP  - 307
EP  - 334
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/12/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/1042-9573(91)90003-I
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/104295739190003I
AB  - This paper uses firm-level panel data to investigate the proposition that reliquification is an important phase of the business cycle. It occurs late during recessions and is characterized by prolonged reductions in real investment, caused by firms needing to accumulate assets in order to improve their financial health. The paper concludes that a buildup of assets precedes an increase in investment. This effect is more important for firms without access to organized bond markets and during recession years.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The pricing of retail deposits: Concentration and information
AU  - Allen, Linda
AU  - Saunders, Anthony
AU  - Udell, Gregory F
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 1
IS  - 4
SP  - 335
EP  - 361
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/12/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/1042-9573(91)90004-J
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/104295739190004J
AB  - The traditional structure-conduct-performance (SCP) hypothesis relates concentration and the mean level of prices but ignores the dispersion of prices around their mean levels. This paper tests two hypotheses which are capable of explaining both the mean and the dispersion of elements in the pricing vector of retail banks—a concentration/collusion-based hypothesis and an asymmetric information-based hypothesis. Evidence is found that the dispersion of bank fees across banks may be due to both market structure and information reasons. The level of bank fees appears to be generally insignificantly related to concentration.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Intermediation and the market for interest rate swaps
AU  - Campbell, Tim S
AU  - Kracaw, William A
JO  - Journal of Financial Intermediation
VL  - 1
IS  - 4
SP  - 362
EP  - 384
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/12/01/
SN  - 1042-9573
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/1042-9573(91)90005-K
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/104295739190005K
AB  - This paper analyzes the role of financial intermediaries as marketmakers in the market for interest rate swaps. We argue that intermediaries which hold large nontraded portfolios of swaps are efficient alternatives to direct hedging by counterparties in publicly traded cash and futures instruments. The efficiency afforded by the swap marketmaker derives from reduction in transactions costs, diversification of basis risk, and reduced agency costs of debt. The analysis provides an explanation for the existence and success of the swaps market as a means for spreading risk and for its dominance by large financial institutions.
